00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:35.770
it writing your own
finite volume code.

00:01:35.770 --> 00:01:39.350
And I want to warn you.

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:43.380
This problem has a
characteristic length

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:50.950
that's way smaller than the
dimensions of the problem.

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:54.270
And so in principle,
you might need

00:01:54.270 --> 00:01:57.510
to use an incredibly
fine mesh to resolve

00:01:57.510 --> 00:01:59.540
the gradients in the problem.

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:03.600
So just remember, in case
you haven't looked at it,

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:05.670
the problem is we
have a drug patch.

00:02:05.670 --> 00:02:07.770
It has some concentration
of the drug.

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:11.960
The drug is diffusing slowly
out of the patch into the flow,

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:15.720
and we have some
flow here like that.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:18.342
And the characteristic
length is at the--

00:02:18.342 --> 00:02:20.950
this is a velocity
boundary layer.

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:23.670
So the velocity
in the x-direction

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:33.520
is equal to y times
something, dv dy, I guess.

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:37.590
This is some number, and
so this has units of--

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:45.780
what is that-- per second,
so like a strain rate, OK?

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:51.210
And the diffusion here is
controlled by diffusivity D,

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:55.690
and that has units of, say,
centimeter squared per second.

00:02:55.690 --> 00:03:04.710
And so the D over
dvx dy, this thing

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:10.350
gives a characteristic
length squared,

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:13.840
which is sort of the natural
length scale of this problem.

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.182
And the problem is that
for the drug molecule,

00:03:17.182 --> 00:03:18.015
it's a big molecule.

00:03:18.015 --> 00:03:20.390
It has a very small diffusivity.

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:23.740
And so therefore, this
is a really tiny ratio,

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:25.750
and so the L is very small.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:29.400
And similarly, if you
look at it from the point

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:31.800
of view in the x-direction,
the Peclet number

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:33.417
is really gigantic.

00:03:33.417 --> 00:03:36.000
And so both of those will tell
you that you have to watch out,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.125
there might be very sharp
gradients in the problem.

00:03:38.125 --> 00:03:41.400
And if you just think of it
physically, right over here

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:44.189
we think the concentration's
0, somewhere over here.

00:03:44.189 --> 00:03:46.230
And all of a sudden right
here, the concentration

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:48.600
is going to be close to the
concentration in the patch.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:49.980
So there's almost
a discontinuity

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:51.730
in the concentration.

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:55.032
So there's a really sharp
gradient on the upstream edge.

00:03:55.032 --> 00:03:57.240
And then something funky is
going to happen down here

00:03:57.240 --> 00:03:58.070
at the end of the patch, too.

00:03:58.070 --> 00:04:00.660
It won't be quite as abrupt,
but could be pretty strange.

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:04.370
All right, so you got it?

00:04:04.370 --> 00:04:04.870
OK.

00:04:07.546 --> 00:04:09.420
And in the problem, we
want you to figure out

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:12.590
the drug diffusing all the
way over to here somewhere,

00:04:12.590 --> 00:04:14.010
way far over there.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:17.670
And so you may need quite a few
mesh points in the y-direction

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:19.330
as well.

00:04:19.330 --> 00:04:19.829
All right.

00:04:19.829 --> 00:04:24.690
And this kind of problem, this
is a very simple case, right?

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:26.970
There's no reactions.

00:04:26.970 --> 00:04:28.725
The velocity's just
in one direction,

00:04:28.725 --> 00:04:30.414
and this is not
a very hard case.

00:04:30.414 --> 00:04:31.830
But you'll see
it's actually still

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:33.910
pretty tricky to get
the right solution.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:36.660
So don't just believe
what the code tells you.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:38.580
Just run COMSOL and just--

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:40.860
don't believe it's
showing the truth.

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.770
And don't believe you just
write down some finite volumes

00:04:43.770 --> 00:04:45.045
that you'll get the truth.

00:04:45.045 --> 00:04:47.170
So mess around with it and
try to convince yourself

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:48.090
it's really converged,
and you really

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:49.423
have the real physical solution.

00:04:51.532 --> 00:04:52.990
Because we expect
a sharp gradient,

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:54.660
say, in the upstream
edge, you might

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.590
want to play with using a
finer mesh in the x-direction

00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:02.350
here than you would down here,
because down here presumably

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:04.560
the gradients in x-direction
are much smaller.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:08.490
So you don't have to use
square finite volumes.

00:05:08.490 --> 00:05:09.960
You could use rectangles.

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:11.005
Yes?

