00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:10.140
And this should be--

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:12.420
this is-- suppose
you choose this

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:16.420
is c equal 0 boundary
condition for this wall,

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:19.840
then this should
be an upper bound.

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:22.540
Because if you put an
absorbing layer here,

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.930
it should drive the
diffusion faster, right?

00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:30.356
So as you increase
this distance--

00:07:30.356 --> 00:07:32.260
let's call it little h--

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.697
as you increase
little h, you should

00:07:34.697 --> 00:07:36.280
converge to the true
solution that you

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:39.252
want sort of from above.

00:07:39.252 --> 00:07:41.641
Does that makes sense?

00:07:41.641 --> 00:07:43.072
Yeah?

00:07:43.072 --> 00:07:45.230
Is this OK?

00:07:45.230 --> 00:07:46.730
All right.

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:50.330
And similarly, you
can vary the mesh,

00:07:50.330 --> 00:07:53.666
how big your boxes are,
say, in delta x and delta y.

00:07:53.666 --> 00:07:55.040
And again, for
each of those, you

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:58.070
could think about how
should things converge.

00:07:58.070 --> 00:07:59.690
And so look and see
if it's actually

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:02.516
converging the way you think
it should be converging, right?

00:08:06.460 --> 00:08:08.589
Any more questions about this?

00:08:08.589 --> 00:08:10.630
OK, so this problem might--
this homework problem

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:13.119
might look like a
MATLAB coding problem.

00:08:13.119 --> 00:08:14.910
It has MATLAB coding,
but it's not really--

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:16.237
that's not really what it is.

00:08:16.237 --> 00:08:17.070
It's really like a--

00:08:17.070 --> 00:08:20.113
it's a conceptual problem
about what you're doing.

00:08:20.113 --> 00:08:22.879
All right.

00:08:22.879 --> 00:08:26.020
All right, in this problem, I
want you to use finite volumes.

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:28.020
So let's talk about finite
volumes for a minute.

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:33.890
So finite volumes is to imagine
that we have little control

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:38.880
volumes, and each one of them
has a little propeller in it,

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:43.200
stirs it up, like little CSTRs.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:45.670
And so we do it just like you
did back in your intro ChemE

00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:48.820
class and mass/energy
balances a million years ago.

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:51.640
You know that you have
some flow coming in here,

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:54.120
and maybe some flow
going out there.

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:56.895
And maybe you have
some flux come in here

00:08:56.895 --> 00:08:59.370
and maybe something out there.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:02.400
And you can add up all the
flows in and all the flows out,

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:05.350
and then that--

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:08.750
the net of all
these fluxes has got

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:10.560
to be equal to the accumulation.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:12.480
And if we're doing a
steady-state problem,

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.600
then there's no time derivative,
so the accumulation term

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:16.662
should be 0.

00:09:16.662 --> 00:09:18.120
And you did a lot
of these problems

00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:19.920
a long time ago, right?

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:21.296
OK, so you just do it like that.

00:09:21.296 --> 00:09:23.920
The only problem is now we have
a million of these little boxes

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:25.003
all coupled to each other.

00:09:25.003 --> 00:09:27.290
So you get one
equation for each box.

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:30.189
And in this problem,
we're going to--

00:09:30.189 --> 00:09:31.980
when you do this method,
what people assume

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:33.646
is that you have a
uniform concentration

00:09:33.646 --> 00:09:35.100
sort of across
here or the number

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:37.740
you use as the average of
the concentration in the cell

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:38.830
as [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:42.959
And so it's not really
exactly realistic.

00:09:42.959 --> 00:09:44.500
So that's where the
approximation is.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:45.720
What you're doing
at the boundaries

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:47.550
is very realistic, because
you're actually computing

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:48.930
the fluxes across
control volumes

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:50.880
is exactly the way
you should do it.

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:55.320
So there's different methods,
right, finite element,

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:57.204
finite difference,
finite volume.

00:09:57.204 --> 00:09:58.620
The nice thing
about finite volume

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:00.660
is you're really
treating exactly what's

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:04.750
happening across the boundaries
of the mesh area, the mesh

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.079
volume.

00:10:06.079 --> 00:10:08.120
And we'll find that a lot
of ChemE problems, this

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:09.369
is how people prefer to do it.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:17.610
And because you're treating
the fluxes exactly,

00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:26.522
if you have your mesh
volume sitting on the wall

00:10:26.522 --> 00:10:28.022
or on top of the
drug patch, suppose

00:10:28.022 --> 00:10:32.380
if we're sitting right on
top of the drug patch here.

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:34.600
Then if you're sitting--

00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:35.650
first, let's do a wall.

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:37.730
Suppose you're sitting
on an impermeable wall,

00:10:37.730 --> 00:10:46.360
then we just know that the flux
here will be 0 if it's a wall.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:47.450
So that's easy.

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:48.247
No flux here.

00:10:48.247 --> 00:10:50.330
So we only have to worry
about this one, this one,

00:10:50.330 --> 00:10:51.750
and this one.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:54.280
That one's not doing anything.

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:57.170
This case, if you say in the
drug patch there is a flux,

00:10:57.170 --> 00:10:59.350
stuff's coming in
and you'll need

00:10:59.350 --> 00:11:02.180
to figure out how to write
that boundary condition.

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:06.100
So the boundary condition as
written is that C, the drug,

00:11:06.100 --> 00:11:11.200
is equal to some number, C
drug, whatever is in the patch.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:14.270
But that's not so
easy to impose here.

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:16.010
And so there's two
ways to look at it.

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:20.110
One way is people compute
this flux by considering--

00:11:23.225 --> 00:11:26.451
suppose I know this
is C drug here.

00:11:26.451 --> 00:11:28.340
I'm trying to really
figure out what's

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:31.200
the average concentration here.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.470
And so one way to
compute this is

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:43.020
to say it's the diffusivity
times C drug minus C

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:50.620
the middle over delta y over 2.

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:52.350
That would be the flux.

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:54.060
So that's one way to look at it.

00:11:54.060 --> 00:11:57.830
Another way people
look at it is they draw

00:11:57.830 --> 00:11:59.998
what they call a ghost volume.

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:06.980
And so here, here's my C
that I care about, C middle.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:13.296
Here's C ghost.

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:18.680
And here is the
line between them.

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:20.450
Now, I can use the
same equation here

00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:22.640
that they would
have used before.

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:25.730
But I don't know what C
ghost is, because there's

00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:26.520
no real cell here.

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:27.590
This is below the patch.

00:12:27.590 --> 00:12:30.350
Here's the patch.

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:32.660
But imagine the patch is
not there for a second,

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:35.660
and I write down the same
equation I would have here.

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:41.730
And the flux diffusively would
have been D C ghost minus C

00:12:41.730 --> 00:12:46.440
middle over delta y.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:49.220
That's what you would have
written as the diffusive flux.

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:51.285
And I don't know
what C ghost is.

00:12:51.285 --> 00:12:52.660
So now, I have to
think about how

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:55.040
do I estimate what C ghost is.

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:59.420
I can say, well, let's
do a linear interpolation

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:02.420
from this concentration
to that concentration.

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:10.520
So let's say that the C
boundary is equal to C

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:15.120
ghost, the average of these
two, plus C mid over 2.

00:13:17.695 --> 00:13:19.820
That's what we got if we
did a linear interpolation

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:22.324
between these two guys to
figure out what it is here.

00:13:22.324 --> 00:13:23.490
But here we know what it is.

00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:25.350
We know what a C boundary is.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:27.620
That's the concentration
of the drug patch

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:29.676
so that we can solve
for what c ghost is.

00:13:29.676 --> 00:13:32.160
AUDIENCE: How do you
know what C middle is?

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:34.512
WILLIAM GREEN, JR: C
middle is the unknown.

00:13:34.512 --> 00:13:35.970
That's what we're
going to compute.

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.428
We just want an equation that
involves C middle, because we

00:13:38.428 --> 00:13:39.595
have c middle as an unknown.

00:13:39.595 --> 00:13:41.344
We need an equation
the involves C middle,

00:13:41.344 --> 00:13:42.585
just like we would for--

00:13:42.585 --> 00:13:43.260
if we have a--

00:13:46.874 --> 00:13:50.050
If we have finite volume that
is in the interior somewhere,

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:53.790
we have c of this
grid point, Cij.

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:55.691
We just want equations
that involve Cij.

00:13:55.691 --> 00:13:57.690
But we need an equation
that somehow connects it

00:13:57.690 --> 00:13:58.620
to the boundary conditions.

00:13:58.620 --> 00:13:59.120
Yeah.

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:01.710
AUDIENCE: When would you
use that second [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.959
if you know C
boundary [INAUDIBLE]??

00:14:04.959 --> 00:14:06.000
WILLIAM GREEN, JR: Right.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.610
And actually, I think if you
do it this way, in this case,

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:10.361
you get the same formula.

00:14:10.361 --> 00:14:11.360
You're running out of C.

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:15.168
AUDIENCE: So when would
you use the C ghost?

00:14:15.168 --> 00:14:18.230
WILLIAM GREEN, JR:
The C ghost thing is

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:22.020
handy when these conditions--

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:24.477
actually, in the finite
volumes, this is it.

00:14:24.477 --> 00:14:25.810
I don't think you need to do it.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:27.260
Maybe if you had a flow,
velocity flow here.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:27.500
I don't know.

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:28.500
But you won't in a wall.

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:33.780
So I don't know if, in the
finite difference method,

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:37.140
you can use those ghost points
as well to do the flux gutter

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:37.916
conditions.

00:14:37.916 --> 00:14:39.540
And that's often
useful to do the ghost

00:14:39.540 --> 00:14:42.710
thing for if you have a
symmetry-imposed flux boundary

00:14:42.710 --> 00:14:44.471
condition.

00:14:44.471 --> 00:14:44.970
Yeah.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:48.456
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:50.362 --> 00:14:51.820
WILLIAM GREEN, JR:
That's the flux.

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:53.528
The flux is coming
from across this wall.

00:14:53.528 --> 00:14:55.660
And we'll have to add
that with the flux coming

00:14:55.660 --> 00:14:57.320
this way and the
flux coming this way

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:00.580
and the flux coming this way
to get our total flux, which

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:07.923
is going to net out to 0
instead of C. Is that all right?

00:15:07.923 --> 00:15:10.190
But the other ones, you
all know how to write them?

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:12.225
They're just velocity flows.

00:15:12.225 --> 00:15:14.250
The nice thing about
the finite volume method

00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:22.560
is that when you're trying
to consider the velocity,

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:25.865
the velocity that matters is
actually the velocity here.

00:15:25.865 --> 00:15:29.940
It's the flux that couples the
two finite values together.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:31.860
So your velocity is
being evaluated halfway

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:36.180
between the two
mesh point centers.

00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:38.760
This turns out to make the
whole procedure more numerically

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:41.250
stable.

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:44.400
You compute the flux
by, say, the difference

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.130
between these two.

00:15:46.130 --> 00:15:50.660
And you're implicitly evaluating
right at halfway between.

00:15:50.660 --> 00:15:53.000
Other methods, like
finite difference,

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.240
you're trying to get
the velocity or the flux

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:59.700
at the same point here.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:01.305
And it doesn't really
make much sense,

00:16:01.305 --> 00:16:03.930
from the point of view of trying
to compute how much material's

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:07.210
close to here, to use
the velocity right there.

00:16:07.210 --> 00:16:10.770
And so when you work out
equations, and particularly

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:13.365
the equations that
involve pressure,

00:16:13.365 --> 00:16:17.340
so suppose you try to discretize
the Navier-Stokes equations

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:20.470
and you have a pressure gradient
that's driving the flow,

00:16:20.470 --> 00:16:22.820
then you have to figure
out where are you

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:25.165
going to evaluate the pressures
and where are you going

00:16:25.165 --> 00:16:26.120
to evaluate the velocities.

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:28.286
And when you try to evaluate
them at the same point,

00:16:28.286 --> 00:16:31.090
it turns out that you get
numerically unstable problems.

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:33.010
But if you do it by this
funny volume method,

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:34.385
then it just works
out naturally.

00:16:34.385 --> 00:16:35.810
It's fine.

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:37.490
And then you need
special methods,

00:16:37.490 --> 00:16:39.554
if you're going to try
to do it where you have

00:16:39.554 --> 00:16:41.970
the velocity of the mesh at
the same point as the pressure

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:42.990
mesh.

00:16:42.990 --> 00:16:44.460
You'll notice in most of
the problems we give you,

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:45.585
we just leave pressure out.

00:16:45.585 --> 00:16:48.420
We try to rewrite the equations
so no pressure ever appears.

00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:50.003
And that's because
pressure in general

00:16:50.003 --> 00:16:55.080
is a problem, because you can
have acoustic waves physically.

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:57.647
And if you do the equations,
which allow for acoustic waves,

00:16:57.647 --> 00:16:59.730
you'll get them in the
numerical solution as well.

00:16:59.730 --> 00:17:01.380
But usually, we don't
care about that.

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:04.770
So you have sound waves
racing around your solution,

00:17:04.770 --> 00:17:06.849
and that causes a lot
of trouble numerically.

00:17:06.849 --> 00:17:09.060
So a lot of times, people
rewrite the equations

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:12.984
to try to remove the
pressure from the equation.

00:17:12.984 --> 00:17:14.900
So you write down the
Navier-Stokes equations.

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:16.807
You guys did this transport.

00:17:16.807 --> 00:17:19.140
Maybe you'll study that today
in the class, in the test.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:19.681
I don't know.

00:17:19.681 --> 00:17:22.790
Anyway, there's a pressure term
if you just write naturally.

00:17:22.790 --> 00:17:25.910
But oftentimes, you can remove
that by an equation of state,

00:17:25.910 --> 00:17:26.780
for example.

00:17:26.780 --> 00:17:28.470
And then you can get rid of it.

00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:31.932
And that turns out to be better
from the numerical solution.

00:17:31.932 --> 00:17:33.380
All right.

00:17:33.380 --> 00:17:33.880
Yes.

