00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:56.030
is it's a linear
differential equation.

00:18:56.030 --> 00:18:59.040
There's no nonlinear term today.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:01.670
So when you rewrite
the equations

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:04.290
of the finite volumes,
it's all going

00:19:04.290 --> 00:19:07.890
to be linear in the unknowns.

00:19:07.890 --> 00:19:10.260
And what else is nice about
this problem, when you use

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:12.720
local finite volumes as your--

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:14.340
It's going to be super-sparse.

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:17.922
So the matrix that comes in
is going to be really sparse.

00:19:17.922 --> 00:19:20.130
And so you'll want to use
some method that can handle

00:19:20.130 --> 00:19:23.610
gigantic sparse matrices.

00:19:23.610 --> 00:19:25.226
So you wrote a code
like that earlier,

00:19:25.226 --> 00:19:26.600
so that would be
