00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:39.510
All right.

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:45.730
What else to tell you about?

00:21:45.730 --> 00:21:50.120
One last thing about
PDEs, and we'll

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:54.020
come back to this later, so
far we haven't done really

00:21:54.020 --> 00:21:56.330
anything that's
very time-dependent.

00:21:56.330 --> 00:22:00.290
But a lot of real world PDEs
have a time dependent in them.

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:02.160
And there's is a very
important concept,

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.470
a thing called the CFL number.

00:22:06.230 --> 00:22:09.230
And this is named
after a 1928 paper,

00:22:09.230 --> 00:22:10.730
and I'll write the
guys' names down.

00:22:21.090 --> 00:22:23.700
And what they showed
was that, if you're

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:27.300
trying to solve the
PDE system, where

00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:32.470
you're discretizing
in both x and time,

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:35.820
that you have a number
that they defined

00:22:35.820 --> 00:22:39.630
as delta t times the
velocity and the extraction

00:22:39.630 --> 00:22:41.920
divided by delta x.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:43.810
So that's a
dimensionless number.

00:22:43.810 --> 00:22:46.560
So that's a CFL number.

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:47.940
You see a lot of
papers that will

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:49.800
say what CFL number they used.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:52.620
What that means is the ratio
of their time mesh compared

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:54.850
to their space mesh.

00:22:54.850 --> 00:23:00.020
And conceptually, let's think
about what's happening here.

00:23:00.020 --> 00:23:02.020
So suppose we have
a flow flowing

00:23:02.020 --> 00:23:06.610
in an upwards direction,
and we have a bunch

00:23:06.610 --> 00:23:08.794
of little finite volumes.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:14.780
So we've discretized
the delta x already.

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:18.250
And this is x.

00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:20.770
And there's a flow here.

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:23.207
And I've already
decided, somehow,

00:23:23.207 --> 00:23:24.540
what length scale I want to use.

00:23:24.540 --> 00:23:26.150
So I've decided my delta x.

00:23:26.150 --> 00:23:29.430
And now, I'm trying to figure
out what delta t I should use.

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:32.180
Now, from the point of
view of saving CPU time

00:23:32.180 --> 00:23:34.670
I want the delta to be
as giant as possible,

00:23:34.670 --> 00:23:37.400
because I want to be able
to zoom along or predict

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:40.350
for long periods of time what's
going to happen in my system.

00:23:40.350 --> 00:23:42.009
But if I make delta
t really large,

00:23:42.009 --> 00:23:43.300
let's think about what happens.

00:23:43.300 --> 00:23:51.980
Suppose I choose delta t to be
10 times delta x divided by u.

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:53.940
So it means that in
my one time step,

00:23:53.940 --> 00:23:57.289
I have some guess or
some current value

00:23:57.289 --> 00:23:59.330
of the concentrations in
all these finite values.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:08.960
And then I wait through
a time step that's

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:12.320
10 times delta x over ux.

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:14.830
So I had some stuff
that was here.

00:24:14.830 --> 00:24:18.320
Where is that going
to be 10 times later?

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:20.877
10 time steps later.

00:24:20.877 --> 00:24:21.710
10 blocks up, right?

00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:26.140
So it's going to be, like,
way up here somewhere.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:29.680
And so what's going
to happen there

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:34.980
is that my numerical methods
are all computing stuff locally

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:36.860
from the spatial derivatives.

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:39.860
But it's crazy if,
between my time steps,

00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:42.140
this stuff completely
left the picture.

00:24:42.140 --> 00:24:44.726
It's already convected all
the way off the screen.

00:24:44.726 --> 00:24:46.850
And some new stuff, which
was way down here before,

00:24:46.850 --> 00:24:48.624
is now the stuff that's here.

00:24:48.624 --> 00:24:50.880
Should be there
if I was physical.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:54.120
Numerically, who knows what will
happen if you try to do this.

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:56.130
But it won't be good.

00:24:56.130 --> 00:24:59.040
So the condition
is that you need

00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:03.060
this number to be less than
1, or same order of magnitude

00:25:03.060 --> 00:25:06.081
as 1, and you try to make
this much bigger than 1,

00:25:06.081 --> 00:25:08.080
then you're doing something
crazy because you're

00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:13.210
convecting stuff over
multiple mesh points.

00:25:13.210 --> 00:25:16.649
And so that turns out to be a
very serious limitation if you

00:25:16.649 --> 00:25:18.190
try to do simulations
for, let's say,

00:25:18.190 --> 00:25:21.070
a reacting flow for a
long period of time,

00:25:21.070 --> 00:25:23.480
because you might have to
use a really tiny delta t.

00:25:23.480 --> 00:25:27.010
And then people have developed
all different fancy methods

00:25:27.010 --> 00:25:28.720
to try to get around that.

00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:32.170
But if you just do the
obvious things to do,

00:25:32.170 --> 00:25:33.805
you'll always run
into this limitation.

00:25:33.805 --> 00:25:37.970
Then you need to choose
the time steps small.

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:43.190
And also, it's bad, because as
you make delta x smaller, which

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:45.780
improves your accuracy,
You'll have to make

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:47.720
your delta t's smaller, too.

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:50.690
But of course, making delta x
smaller increases your CPU time

00:25:50.690 --> 00:25:53.360
because you have more
finite volumes to compute.

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:55.040
And then you'll also have to
make double t smaller, which

00:25:55.040 --> 00:25:55.910
means you'll have to do
more time steps, too.

00:25:55.910 --> 00:25:58.040
So it's even like
a double whammy.

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:01.400
So getting more accuracy is
going to really cost you badly.

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:05.520
And so this another reason
why people used to always

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:06.862
refer to color fluid dynamics.

00:26:06.862 --> 00:26:08.820
You can make a pretty
picture, but it might not

00:26:08.820 --> 00:26:09.935
be physical at all.

00:26:09.935 --> 00:26:12.060
Because you can make it
solve equations that maybe,

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:13.470
for example, didn't
impose this, then

00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:14.970
who knows what kind of
crazy stuff you'll get.

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:16.050
You'll got something.

00:26:16.050 --> 00:26:18.000
It'll compute something,
but it may have no relation

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:18.833
to the real problem.

00:26:23.104 --> 00:26:24.770
I think that's all I
was say about PDEs.

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:26.811
Are there any questions
about PDEs before I start

00:26:26.811 --> 00:26:28.128
talking about probability?

00:26:30.811 --> 00:26:31.810
You got it totally down.

00:26:31.810 --> 00:26:34.018
I'm looking forward to some
really awesome solutions.

00:26:34.018 --> 00:26:34.887
How about that?

00:26:44.940 --> 00:26:46.090
Just one last comment.

00:26:46.090 --> 00:26:48.550
If you decide you wanted
to do adaptive meshing

00:26:48.550 --> 00:26:53.380
and you want to
change your mesh size,

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:56.369
you can choose measures
like this if you want.

00:26:56.369 --> 00:26:57.910
And you can even do
things like this,

00:26:57.910 --> 00:26:58.940
where you have a
bigger mesh, and then

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:00.731
maybe have two smaller
meshes underneath it

00:27:00.731 --> 00:27:03.040
in the next trial.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:05.120
So you can just have
stuff flowing here,

00:27:05.120 --> 00:27:08.557
stuff flowing here
stuff flowing there.

00:27:08.557 --> 00:27:10.390
So you can do all kinds
of crazy stuff like.

00:27:10.390 --> 00:27:13.870
This can really help improve the
accuracy of the solution a lot.

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:16.300
But it's, I would say,
very prone to bugs.

00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:18.220
So if you do this,
be really careful

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:19.240
and don't do it too
often, I would say.

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:20.260
You might have a
few boundaries where

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:22.870
you do something funky like
that to change that mesh size.

00:27:22.870 --> 00:27:24.480
But don't go crazy with it.

00:27:24.480 --> 00:27:25.650
[INAUDIBLE] is smart.

00:27:25.650 --> 00:27:27.900
It has a really nice way of
doing the meshing for you.

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:32.170
So that's its advantage, that
somebody very carefully coded

00:27:32.170 --> 00:27:34.660
how to handle this kind of
stuff in a general case.

00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:36.160
But if you guys are doing
it for the first time,

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:37.260
it might not be so good.

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:42.590
So that's enough of PDEs.

00:27:42.590 --> 00:27:45.040
Let's talk about probability.

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:13.750
So probability is everywhere,
except in undergraduate ChemE

00:28:13.750 --> 00:28:14.500
homework problems.

00:28:17.200 --> 00:28:20.142
So when you do problems
as an undergraduate,

00:28:20.142 --> 00:28:21.600
they always had
some nice solution.

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:25.050
It was 2 pi, it was 3.0.

00:28:25.050 --> 00:28:27.580
Everything was, like,
deterministic, is definite.

00:28:27.580 --> 00:28:29.182
The grader could go through.

00:28:29.182 --> 00:28:30.265
Oh, no, you're off by 0.1.

00:28:30.265 --> 00:28:33.820
It couldn't possibly be right.

00:28:33.820 --> 00:28:35.050
That's, like, not reality.

00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:37.300
So any time you actually
make a measurement,

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:38.855
you always had
measurement noise.

00:28:38.855 --> 00:28:40.480
And if you try to
repeat a measurement,

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:42.340
you don't get the same
result. So that's,

00:28:42.340 --> 00:28:45.630
like, completely different
than an undergraduate problem.

00:28:45.630 --> 00:28:47.120
But this is the reality.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:51.480
So the reality is the world is,
like, not so nice as you think.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:53.191
But actually, it's
even more fundamental.

00:28:53.191 --> 00:28:54.690
It's nothing about--
I mean, there's

00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:56.440
one problem about how
good an experimental

00:28:56.440 --> 00:28:59.550
those people are, and
how fancy an apparatus

00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:03.240
you bought that can make
things exactly reproducible.

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:06.720
But even if you do that
perfectly, the equations we

00:29:06.720 --> 00:29:10.590
use really don't correspond
to the real physical reality.

00:29:10.590 --> 00:29:12.765
So we always use the
continuum equations.

00:29:12.765 --> 00:29:16.680
You guys probably are studying
them a lot in 1040 and 1050,

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:19.314
especially 1050, I guess.

00:29:19.314 --> 00:29:20.730
But those equations
are really all

00:29:20.730 --> 00:29:24.330
derived from averages
over ensembles

00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:26.190
or little finite
volumes or something

00:29:26.190 --> 00:29:29.760
if you look at the
derivation of the equations.

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:33.830
And reality is that the
world is full of molecules.

00:29:33.830 --> 00:29:38.160
And so they're all
wiggling around.

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:39.930
And if you look in a
little finite volume,

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:41.280
you look right now,
you'll see that there's

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:42.520
27 molecules in there.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:44.690
If you look a second
later, there might be 28.

00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:46.770
Then a little later, maybe 26.

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:49.770
It's always fluctuating around.

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:52.860
But according to our average
equations that we use,

00:29:52.860 --> 00:29:56.805
like in the Navier-Stokes
equations, it always 27.3.

00:29:56.805 --> 00:29:58.680
But of course, there's
not 0.3 of a molecule.

00:29:58.680 --> 00:30:00.980
So, I mean, explicitly,
it's the average

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:03.750
is what we're computing,
and the reality

00:30:03.750 --> 00:30:06.520
is fluctuating around the edges.

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:08.250
Same thing in thermo.

00:30:08.250 --> 00:30:11.490
We say that such-and-such has
a certain amount of energy.

00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:14.970
But you guys have some
[INAUDIBLE] already, yes?

00:30:14.970 --> 00:30:17.250
So you saw that's not true?

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:19.180
So really, all that's
saying is that's, like,

00:30:19.180 --> 00:30:20.660
the probability, the average.

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:24.112
If you've had many,
many ensembles that

00:30:24.112 --> 00:30:26.070
were exactly the same
and you average them all,

00:30:26.070 --> 00:30:28.194
you get some number and
that's your average energy.

00:30:28.194 --> 00:30:30.105
But for any actual
realization, it

00:30:30.105 --> 00:30:31.730
has some different
value of the energy.

00:30:35.380 --> 00:30:37.680
And it's even worse than that.

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:40.362
That's because we have
a lot of particles.

00:30:40.362 --> 00:30:42.570
You can even go down to,
like, the microscopic level,

00:30:42.570 --> 00:30:44.629
where you have one molecule.

00:30:44.629 --> 00:30:46.670
And you calculate things
about that, it turns out

00:30:46.670 --> 00:30:48.340
you have to use the
Schrodinger equation for that.

00:30:48.340 --> 00:30:49.480
And the Schrodinger
equation explicitly

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:50.725
only gives you
probability densities.

00:30:50.725 --> 00:30:52.270
So it just tells
you the probability

00:30:52.270 --> 00:30:53.800
the molecule might be
somewhere, the electron

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:56.110
might be somewhere, the
energy might be something.

00:30:56.110 --> 00:30:58.240
But it's not actually
whether it really is.

00:30:58.240 --> 00:31:00.430
It's just saying a
probability distribution.

00:31:00.430 --> 00:31:02.638
And every time you do the
experiment on the molecule,

00:31:02.638 --> 00:31:04.090
you get a different result.

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:07.190
Now, this is super-annoying,
but it's the way life is.

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:09.190
Einstein got so annoyed,
he has a famous saying,

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:10.606
and it's "God does
not play dice."

00:31:10.606 --> 00:31:13.250
He was, like, just completely
annoyed at these equations.

00:31:13.250 --> 00:31:16.300
But it's the way it is.

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:20.980
So the reality is that things,
all we know about, really,

00:31:20.980 --> 00:31:22.500
are probability distributions.

00:31:22.500 --> 00:31:24.730
In most of our
work, in our lives,

00:31:24.730 --> 00:31:27.799
we always talk about, like,
the mean or the median.

00:31:27.799 --> 00:31:29.590
And we're talking as
if it's a real number.

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:32.470
But really, it's always
some distribution.

00:31:32.470 --> 00:31:34.840
So it's time, I guess,
you're in graduate school,

00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:36.680
it's time to, like,
face up to this.

00:31:36.680 --> 00:31:38.138
And that's what
we're going to talk

00:31:38.138 --> 00:31:39.826
about for the next week or two.

00:31:43.695 --> 00:31:46.774
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:46.774 --> 00:31:48.190
WILLIAM GREEN, JR:
This also makes

00:31:48.190 --> 00:31:49.270
it makes you wonder
what you're doing

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:50.600
when you make a measurement.

00:31:50.600 --> 00:31:53.769
So if you make a measurement,
first of all, the fact

00:31:53.769 --> 00:31:55.560
that when you measure
something repeatedly,

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:58.270
you're not going to get the
same number, that's alarming.

00:31:58.270 --> 00:32:00.640
Because I want to
say I'm 5 foot 9",

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:03.305
this should be pretty
common, I'm always 5 foot 9".

00:32:03.305 --> 00:32:05.680
But actually, if you measure
me multiple times, sometimes

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:07.870
you'll get 5' 9 and 1/4"
Some people will get 5'

00:32:07.870 --> 00:32:13.450
8 and 3/4" So it might make
you worry, did I change?

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:17.620
Did I grow between
the measurements?

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:19.300
So that's one issue.

00:32:23.680 --> 00:32:31.035
Because our experiments
are not repeatable

00:32:31.035 --> 00:32:32.660
and we get different
numbers every time

00:32:32.660 --> 00:32:35.414
we make a measurement,
then we have a big problem.

00:32:35.414 --> 00:32:36.830
Somebody says,
well, I really want

00:32:36.830 --> 00:32:38.720
to know how tall
Professor Green is.

00:32:38.720 --> 00:32:41.299
I've always wondered,
how tall is he?

00:32:41.299 --> 00:32:43.090
And everybody's told
me a different number.

00:32:43.090 --> 00:32:44.465
And when you go
measure it again,

00:32:44.465 --> 00:32:45.860
you get a different
number again.

00:32:45.860 --> 00:32:48.380
What's going on?

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:49.970
And so you'll have
to then-- then we

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:51.740
have, like, a
concept that there is

00:32:51.740 --> 00:32:54.170
a true height of Professor
Green and we just

00:32:54.170 --> 00:32:56.160
don't know what it is.

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:57.950
And then we'll try
maybe to make repeated

00:32:57.950 --> 00:33:01.637
measurements of my height, and
then maybe take the average.

00:33:01.637 --> 00:33:03.220
That would be the
obvious thing to do.

00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:04.952
And we take the average
and report that.

00:33:04.952 --> 00:33:06.910
We'll tell the boss,
we'll lie to him, say, oh,

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:08.395
Professor Green's 5 foot 9".

00:33:08.395 --> 00:33:10.520
When really, we never
actually measured 5' foot 9".

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:14.355
Every time we measured, it was
5' 9 and 1/8", 5' 8 and 3/4".

00:33:14.355 --> 00:33:15.980
Every time, it was
something different.

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:17.470
But we just say, OK, it's 5' 9".

00:33:17.470 --> 00:33:19.400
And the boss, he doesn't want to
know about all this complexity,

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:20.733
anyway, so he just believes you.

00:33:20.733 --> 00:33:22.460
So it takes your average number.

00:33:22.460 --> 00:33:27.290
But you know that you're not
really sure I'm exactly 5' 9"

00:33:27.290 --> 00:33:30.560
And so you have a
probability distribution,

00:33:30.560 --> 00:33:32.280
and you're doing
your best guess.

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:34.310
And in fact, if you're
honest to your boss,

00:33:34.310 --> 00:33:35.170
you'll give him an error bar.

00:33:35.170 --> 00:33:37.211
You'll say he's 5' 9",
plus or minus 1/2 an inch.

00:33:39.980 --> 00:33:41.657
And that way, what
you're saying is

00:33:41.657 --> 00:33:43.865
you're pretty sure the true
height of Professor Green

00:33:43.865 --> 00:33:44.990
is somewhere in that range.

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:48.630
Is this OK?

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:49.260
Yeah.

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:52.760
Now it might be that I'm
actually changing height.

00:33:52.760 --> 00:33:55.010
I get a good night's rest,
I lie down for a long time.

00:33:55.010 --> 00:33:55.820
Maybe when I stretch
out a little bit.

00:33:55.820 --> 00:33:58.195
When I stand up in front of
lecture here for a long time,

00:33:58.195 --> 00:33:59.005
I'm shrinking.

00:33:59.005 --> 00:34:00.380
My vertebrae are
being compressed

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:01.421
by standing here so long.

00:34:01.421 --> 00:34:03.680
So it's, like, a
combination of things.

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:05.870
One is your measurement
system is not perfect,

00:34:05.870 --> 00:34:09.040
and one is that I actually
might be fluctuating.

00:34:09.040 --> 00:34:10.800
I had a big breakfast,
I'm growing.

00:34:13.310 --> 00:34:14.859
So is it true with everything?

00:34:14.859 --> 00:34:16.400
Every experiment
you do is like this,

00:34:16.400 --> 00:34:19.639
that there is a real fluctuation
of the real, physical apparatus

00:34:19.639 --> 00:34:22.340
of the thing that you're trying
to measure because mostly,

00:34:22.340 --> 00:34:24.340
things we're trying to
measure have fluctuations

00:34:24.340 --> 00:34:25.159
intrinsically.

00:34:25.159 --> 00:34:28.570
And then on top of that,
your measurement device

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:30.590
is fluctuating, which
means-- and then

00:34:30.590 --> 00:34:32.298
the combination is
what you're measuring.

00:34:32.298 --> 00:34:35.270
It gives you fluctuation.

00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:36.949
If you have a very
nice instrument,

00:34:36.949 --> 00:34:38.719
the fluctuation
of your instrument

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:41.239
is smaller than the
fluctuation in the real system

00:34:41.239 --> 00:34:42.830
and you'll go down to the limit.

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:44.000
Anybody with a really
good instrument

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:45.920
should measure approximately the
same probability distribution,

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:47.544
which is actually
the real fluctuation.

00:34:47.544 --> 00:34:48.760
My height, for example.

00:34:48.760 --> 00:34:50.385
So if you bought a
laser interferometer

00:34:50.385 --> 00:34:53.389
and mounted a mirror on my
head, and measured my height

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:55.130
to the wavelength
of light, you're

00:34:55.130 --> 00:34:57.080
pretty sure that
it's pretty good.

00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:58.880
It's within a
wavelength of light.

00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:00.796
So the error bar there
is just due to the fact

00:35:00.796 --> 00:35:02.620
that I slouch sometimes.

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:03.450
Is that OK?

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:09.650
So let's talk about some basic
things about probability.

00:35:09.650 --> 00:35:13.850
So we're always saying there's
a probability of an event.

00:35:19.710 --> 00:35:21.500
And so we want to give a number.

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:23.570
So for example,
I'm flipping coins.

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:26.360
I flip a penny, it
could be heads or tails.

00:35:26.360 --> 00:35:31.902
I'll say the
probability of heads

00:35:31.902 --> 00:35:35.950
is approximately equal to 1/2.

00:35:35.950 --> 00:35:42.230
So I flipped the coin, and if
you flip the coin 100 times,

00:35:42.230 --> 00:35:43.880
you might expect
to see 50 heads.

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:47.600
Now, it could be 49 heads,
it could be 51 heads.

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:50.060
So you have to worry about,
like, exactly how precisely you

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:50.560
know it.

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:52.750
But you think it's
something like a half.

00:35:52.750 --> 00:35:55.700
Now, just to warn
you, I actually

00:35:55.700 --> 00:35:58.830
didn't specify any more
significant figures here,

00:35:58.830 --> 00:36:00.750
and it might be really
hard to figure out what

00:36:00.750 --> 00:36:02.312
those significant figures are.

00:36:02.312 --> 00:36:04.270
And this is related to
the measurement problem.

00:36:04.270 --> 00:36:07.620
So we think that a coin
has about a 50/50 chance

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:08.880
of being heads or tails.

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:10.700
But if you really
wanted to prove it,

00:36:10.700 --> 00:36:13.090
that might be really hard to do.

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:15.268
You can have joint
probabilities.

00:36:20.890 --> 00:36:27.640
So suppose I have a
penny and I have a dime.

00:36:27.640 --> 00:36:30.430
And I try to think, if I flipped
them both, what could happen?

00:36:30.430 --> 00:36:33.194
I could have that they
both come up heads.

00:36:33.194 --> 00:36:35.360
I could have this guy come
up heads, this guy tails.

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:38.470
This guy tails,
this heads, tails.

00:36:38.470 --> 00:36:40.504
So there's, like, four
possible outcomes,

00:36:40.504 --> 00:36:42.420
and we think they all
have about approximately

00:36:42.420 --> 00:36:43.815
equal probabilities.

00:36:43.815 --> 00:36:45.940
So the probability of any
of these things happening

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:46.773
should be about 1/4.

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:59.560
So you can write the probability
of event 1 and event 2.

00:37:02.320 --> 00:37:04.330
So this would be, for
example, the probability

00:37:04.330 --> 00:37:08.180
that I got heads for
penny and heads for dime,

00:37:08.180 --> 00:37:09.850
and I think that
this is about 1/4.

00:37:19.276 --> 00:37:32.802
Now, I could also say
the probability of heads,

00:37:32.802 --> 00:37:37.620
and heads is equal to
the probability of heads

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:45.090
for the penny times the
probability of heads

00:37:45.090 --> 00:37:53.090
for the dime if I got
heads for the penny.

00:37:53.090 --> 00:37:58.860
Now, if these two coin flips
are completely uncorrelated,

00:37:58.860 --> 00:38:02.310
then the probability of heads on
the dime and heads on the penny

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:02.830
is the same.

00:38:02.830 --> 00:38:04.955
It's just the probability
of the heads on the dime.

00:38:04.955 --> 00:38:06.390
So they don't matter.

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:09.992
But many things that we'll
study are correlated.

00:38:09.992 --> 00:38:11.700
That the probability
of something happens

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:13.650
depends on whether
something else happened.

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:19.780
So this kind of expression
is very important.

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:21.080
Now, this is just an equality.

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:24.070
It's like a definition
of what these are, right?

00:38:24.070 --> 00:38:26.320
And I'll just notice you
can write that the other way

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:26.830
around.

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:31.550
So it's the probability
of heads on the dime

00:38:31.550 --> 00:38:34.780
