00:46:50.142 --> 00:46:54.600
times the probability
of Ai divided

00:46:54.600 --> 00:47:06.722
by the sum of the probability
of Aj [INAUDIBLE] Aj.

00:47:11.710 --> 00:47:14.112
And this is the form that
you'll normally see based here.

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:23.370
A lot of times, we have a
continuous variable instead

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:25.910
of discrete events like this.

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:28.320
And so then we talk about
probability distributions.

00:47:31.240 --> 00:47:33.980
And so instead of
having a sum there,

00:47:33.980 --> 00:47:36.310
we might have an integral.

00:47:36.310 --> 00:47:42.400
And this is a topic that also is
quite confusing to many people.

00:47:46.060 --> 00:47:51.956
So suppose I had a
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution.

00:47:51.956 --> 00:47:56.710
And I have, like, the
probability density

00:47:56.710 --> 00:48:00.420
of having a certain velocity
in the extraction instead

00:48:00.420 --> 00:48:02.440
of the particle.

00:48:02.440 --> 00:48:05.760
And so that's going
to be something like e

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:12.834
to the negative 1/2 mvx squared
over keT divided by something.

00:48:15.663 --> 00:48:17.246
And maybe it actually
is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:48:17.246 --> 00:48:18.080
I'm not sure.

00:48:18.080 --> 00:48:19.730
Maybe there's a vx here.

00:48:19.730 --> 00:48:20.900
Something like that.

00:48:20.900 --> 00:48:22.435
So you have an
expression that you

00:48:22.435 --> 00:48:24.470
get for [INAUDIBLE] for
probability density.

00:48:24.470 --> 00:48:25.970
Now, what does this mean?

00:48:25.970 --> 00:48:28.550
We want this thing
to be the integral

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:34.377
of P of vx dvx over from
negative infinity to infinity.

00:48:34.377 --> 00:48:35.710
We want this to equal something.

00:48:35.710 --> 00:48:37.910
What do we want this to equal?

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:39.120
1.

00:48:39.120 --> 00:48:42.176
So that means that the
units of this, this

00:48:42.176 --> 00:48:44.709
is units of
centimeters per second,

00:48:44.709 --> 00:48:45.750
what's the units of this?

00:48:45.750 --> 00:48:49.630
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:53.370
WILLIAM GREEN, JR: Centimeters
per second now minus 1.

00:48:53.370 --> 00:48:57.860
It's, like, it's
per the unit to this

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:00.190
to get a dimensionless
number there.

00:49:00.190 --> 00:49:05.506
So this has units of
seconds per centimeter,

00:49:05.506 --> 00:49:07.880
which probably none of you
thought until I just said that

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:09.550
to you.

00:49:09.550 --> 00:49:14.030
So probability
densities are tricky,

00:49:14.030 --> 00:49:17.679
and they always have to
be multiplied by a delta.

00:49:17.679 --> 00:49:19.220
When I talk about
this, I really need

00:49:19.220 --> 00:49:23.190
to talk about P of vx, delta vx.

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.670
I need to have something
here to make this look

00:49:25.670 --> 00:49:27.470
like a probability again.

00:49:27.470 --> 00:49:29.390
And so the issue is
that the probability

00:49:29.390 --> 00:49:32.354
that the velocity is exactly
something is, like, 0.

00:49:32.354 --> 00:49:33.770
It's really the
probability that's

00:49:33.770 --> 00:49:37.630
in a certain range,
plus or minus something.

00:49:37.630 --> 00:49:39.145
Then you get a
nonzero probability.

00:49:43.372 --> 00:49:44.830
There's another
quantity you'll see

00:49:44.830 --> 00:49:49.030
a lot called the cumulative
probability distribution.

00:49:49.030 --> 00:49:50.460
Let's see, what letter do I use?

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:56.650
Call it F. And this would
be like the integral

00:49:56.650 --> 00:50:03.634
from negative infinity to
vx prime, or vx of P over vx

00:50:03.634 --> 00:50:07.330
prime, dvx prime.

00:50:07.330 --> 00:50:09.880
And this is the probability
that the particle

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:11.830
has vx less than something.

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:19.492
So this is F is equal to
the probability that vx--

00:50:19.492 --> 00:50:21.620
let's call this vx star--

00:50:21.620 --> 00:50:26.520
vx is less than or
equal to vx star.

00:50:26.520 --> 00:50:28.520
And that can be quite
an important property.

00:50:28.520 --> 00:50:32.236
So for example, you're
designing a supersonic nozzle.

00:50:32.236 --> 00:50:34.110
You want to know what
gas molecules are going

00:50:34.110 --> 00:50:36.152
to come out at a certain speed.

00:50:36.152 --> 00:50:37.860
You really need to
know that probability.

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:40.565
How many of them are going to
be bigger than that speed, how

00:50:40.565 --> 00:50:43.320
many less than that speed?

00:50:43.320 --> 00:50:47.562
So these are two different ways
to express a similar thing.

00:50:47.562 --> 00:50:49.020
This is, like, the
probably that it

00:50:49.020 --> 00:50:51.550
does have that speed
within a certain range.

00:50:51.550 --> 00:50:54.240
This is the probability that
it has anything less than

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:55.680
or equal to that speed.

00:50:55.680 --> 00:50:58.020
And in a completely different
way, this is an integral.

00:50:58.020 --> 00:51:02.640
This has units of dimensionless.

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:06.400
This has units of per velocity.

